  "local_port": 55980,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I was fired from my job and my boss didn't give me a reason why he fired me. In future job interviews how should I answer why I left my last job?",
  "response": "When discussing why you left your last job in future interviews, it\u2019s important to be honest yet tactful, and to focus on moving forward positively. Since your boss didn\u2019t provide a reason for your termination, you can frame your response in a way that emphasizes your professionalism and eagerness to grow. Here\u2019s how you could approach it:\n\n1. **Keep it brief and neutral**:  \n   \"Unfortunately, my employment with [Company Name] ended unexpectedly. I wasn\u2019t given a specific reason for the decision, but I\u2019m using this as an opportunity to grow and find a role where I can contribute more effectively.\"\n\n2. **Focus on the future**:  \n   \"While my leaving [Company Name] wasn\u2019t my choice, I\u2019m excited to bring my skills and experience to a new opportunity. I\u2019m particularly interested in this role because [mention something specific about the job/company].\"\n\n3. **Highlight your strengths and lessons learned**:  \n   \"Although my time at [Company Name] ended unexpectedly, I gained valuable experience and skills that I\u2019m eager to apply in a new position. I\u2019m committed to finding a role where I can make a positive impact and continue to grow professionally.\"\n\n4. **Avoid negativity**:  \n   Resist the urge to speak negatively about your former employer or boss, even if you feel wronged. Staying professional demonstrates maturity and emotional intelligence.\n\n5. **Be prepared for follow-up questions**:  \n   Employers may ask for more details, but you can redirect the conversation to your skills and qualifications:  \n   \"I didn\u2019t receive a clear explanation for the decision, but I\u2019ve reflected on my time there and am confident in the skills I\u2019ve developed. I\u2019m ready to apply those in a new environment.\"\n\nBy keeping your response professional, focusing on your strengths, and showing enthusiasm for the new opportunity, you can turn a challenging situation into a positive narrative.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
